\begin{MintedVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
History mechanism

\PYG{k}{1.} The central regulatory body\PYGZsq{}s aggressive monetary tightening cycle, raising the base lending rate from approximately 0.25\PYGZpc{} in early 2022 to approximately 5.3\PYGZpc{} by mid\PYGZhy{}2023, created competing pressures on the Urban\PYGZhy{}Industrial Employment Ledger.
\PYG{k}{2.} Post\PYGZhy{}pandemic retention strategies, where firms kept staff despite slowing demand to avoid rehiring costs in a tight environment, suppressed initial claims filing rates below structural equilibrium levels. This phenomenon, combined with historically low resignation rates in 2022, drove the 4\PYGZhy{}week moving average from \PYGZti{}240,000 toward the \PYGZti{}200,000 trough observed in early 2023, well below the pre\PYGZhy{}pandemic structural baseline of \PYGZti{}220,000.
\PYG{k}{3.} As these tight conditions in the Urban\PYGZhy{}Industrial Employment Ledger began to reverse under monetary tightening, the rate hikes began transmitting into tighter financial conditions by mid\PYGZhy{}2023. Rate\PYGZhy{}sensitive sectors, particularly technology, real estate, and financial services, initiated significant layoff cycles. This sector\PYGZhy{}specific shock drove the sharp spike from \PYGZti{}200,000 to \PYGZti{}250,000 between January and July 2023, while more resilient sectors like healthcare and government employment partially offset the broader deterioration.
\PYG{k}{4.} As these layoffs spread and financial conditions remained restrictive, the early\PYGZhy{}2024 reabsorption of workers from tech and financial sectors into healthcare, logistics, and services only partly offset the broader pass\PYGZhy{}through of restrictive credit conditions. As tighter financing and slower hiring spread beyond the first wave of rate\PYGZhy{}sensitive layoffs, initial claims rose again toward the mid\PYGZhy{}230,000s by mid\PYGZhy{}2024 rather than stabilizing at the early\PYGZhy{}2024 trough.
\PYG{k}{5.} The 4\PYGZhy{}week moving average of initial claims within the Urban\PYGZhy{}Industrial Employment Ledger fell from roughly 240,000 in early 2022 to near 200,000 by early 2023, rebounded to about 250,000 by mid\PYGZhy{}2023 as rate\PYGZhy{}sensitive layoffs intensified, eased back toward roughly 200,000\PYGZhy{}205,000 around early 2024, and then climbed again toward roughly 235,000\PYGZhy{}240,000 by mid\PYGZhy{}2024 as restrictive financial conditions continued to broaden across employers.

Forecast mechanism

\PYG{k}{1.} Restrictive monetary policy continues to maintain elevated borrowing costs, with the lagged transmission of high interest rates into business investment and hiring decisions still working through the economy.
\PYG{k}{2.} The sustained inversion of the treasury yield curve through 2024 is projected to continue compressing net interest margins for regional banks, tightening credit availability for small and medium enterprises.
\PYG{k}{3.} Since these enterprises account for a significant part of the Urban\PYGZhy{}Industrial Employment Ledger, credit\PYGZhy{}constrained hiring and episodic layoffs in this segment are expected to generate recurring upward spikes.
\PYG{k}{4.} Given this tightening in credit conditions, sectors that over\PYGZhy{}hired during the 2021\PYGZhy{}2022 expansion, particularly technology, e\PYGZhy{}commerce, and professional services, are projected to continue rightsizing their workforces, contributing to episodic layoff waves that can drive the claims above 240,000.
\PYG{k}{5.} However, the rightsizing\PYGZhy{}driven layoffs remain sector\PYGZhy{}specific rather than economy\PYGZhy{}wide. Continued strength in healthcare, government, and infrastructure hiring partially offsets these losses, keeping the oscillations in the Urban\PYGZhy{}Industrial Employment Ledger from developing into a sustained uptrend, so that spikes toward 240,000\PYGZhy{}246,000 remain temporary rather than establishing a new structural baseline.
\PYG{k}{6.} The 4\PYGZhy{}week moving average of initial claims in the Urban\PYGZhy{}Industrial Employment Ledger is projected to fluctuate within an elevated range through September 2025, with most weekly readings expected to fall between 220,000\PYGZhy{}235,000, reaching a low near 213,000 and a high near 246,000 only at the extremes of the oscillation, with a periodicity of approximately 6\PYGZhy{}8 weeks and no sustained directional trend.
